<Layout title="How to Change Real Estate Agents Mid-Campaign in Brisbane | Daniel Gierach Property" description="A practical guide for Queensland vendors on recognising when an agent relationship isn't working, how to terminate an exclusive agency agreement, and how to manage the transition." draft={draft}>

<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can I cancel my exclusive agency agreement in Queensland?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. You can terminate an exclusive agency agreement in Queensland, but you must follow the process set out in the agreement itself, typically by giving written notice as specified in the termination clause. The notice period is usually 30 days, though it varies. Read your agreement carefully and seek legal advice if you are unsure."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is there a cooling off period when signing an agency agreement?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. In Queensland, vendors have a 1 business day cooling off period after signing a residential property agency agreement. If you change your mind within that period, you can cancel the agreement without penalty. This is a separate right from the buyer's cooling off period under a property contract."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What happens to my existing marketing if I change agents?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Photography, floor plans, and written copy are typically owned by the agent or their contracted suppliers, not the vendor. A new agent will generally re-shoot the property for a fresh presentation rather than use existing materials. This resets your days-on-market appearance and removes the visual association with the previous campaign."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Will I still owe commission to my old agent if I change agents?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Potentially, yes. If your previous agent introduced a buyer who later purchases the property, even after the agreement is terminated, you may owe commission under the original agreement's 'protection period' clause. Read your agreement's terms carefully, and have a solicitor review it if you are concerned."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How long does a typical exclusive agency agreement last in Queensland?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Exclusive agency agreements in Queensland are typically 45 to 90 days. The duration is negotiable before signing. The Property Occupations Act 2014 (QLD) sets out the requirements for these agreements, including the requirement for clear termination provisions."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

